problem_prompt:
You are an expert in number theory. Solve the following problem. What is the largest integer that is a divisor of \[
(n+1)(n+3)(n+5)(n+7)(n+9)
\]for all positive even integers $n$?
solution: Among five consecutive odd numbers, at least one is divisible by 3 and exactly one is divisible by 5, so the product is always divisible by 15. The cases $n=2$, $n=10$, and $n=12$ demonstrate that no larger common divisor is possible, since $\boxed{15}$ is the greatest common divisor of $3\cdot5\cdot7\cdot9\cdot11$, $11\cdot13\cdot15\cdot17\cdot19$, and $13\cdot15\cdot17\cdot19\cdot21$.

By looking at the expression $(n+1)(n+3)(n+5)(n+7)(n+9)$, we can see that every consecutive group of five integers is being multiplied together, starting at $n+1$ and ending at $n+9$. Since we are looking for the largest integer that is a divisor for all positive even integers $n$, we can examine the expressions when $n$ is even.

When $n$ is even, each of the five consecutive integers will include at least one odd number. When we multiply these five numbers together, the product will be odd.

Therefore, for all positive even integers $n$, the expression $(n+1)(n+3)(n+5)(n+7)(n+9)$ will always be odd. The largest integer that is a divisor of all odd numbers is 1, so the answer is $\boxed{1}$.
